{"title_page": "Erik Wallenberg", "text_new": "[[File:Erik Wallenberg inventor of Tetra Pak first package.jpg|thumb|Erik Wallenberg with the tetrahedron package]]\n'''Erik Wallenberg''' (25 December 1915 \u2013 18 October 1999) was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] engineer. He is credited for inventing the [[Tetra Pak]] [[tetrahedron]] packaging in 1944.\n\n==Career==\nWallenberg had initially planned to join the Army as an officer, but fell ill during military training and had to abandon his plans. He was accepted at [[Karolinska Institutet]] medical school in [[Stockholm]], but decided to move to [[Lund]] and try to enter the medical school at [[Lund University]] instead.<ref>Andersson, Peter and Larsson, Tommy, ''Tetra. Historien om dynastin Rausing'', Stockholm: Norstedts 1998 ({{ISBN|91-7263-014-0}}), p. 13</ref>\n\nIn 1943, waiting to get accepted at [[Lund University]], Wallenberg got a job as lab assistant at [[\u00c5kerlund & Rausing]], a local firm manufacturing food packaging. When his manager got drafted in 1944, he became head of the research lab, aged 28.\n\nThe team had orders from the company owner [[Ruben Rausing]] to produce a viable packaging for milk that was cheap enough to compete with the current milk distribution system, based on loose milk sold in reusable glass bottles. The key to this was to use as little packaging material as possible. The research lab had tried and failed a number of different solutions. Finally, reportedly when ill with fever, Wallenberg got the idea of using one single sheet of paper rolled into a cylinder and folded from two different sides, creating a mathematical [[tetrahedron]].<ref>Andersson, Peter and Larsson, Tommy, ''Tetra. Historien om dynastin Rausing'', Stockholm: Norstedts 1998 ({{ISBN|91-7263-014-0}}), p. 18</ref> The volume created only needed to be sealed in three places and the packages could be produced in one subsequent sequence from one roll of paper, using a minimum of material, with a minimum of waste.<ref>[http://www.tekniskamuseet.se/1/1781.html Tetra Pak (Swedish)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926034133/http://www.tekniskamuseet.se/1/1781.html |date=26 September 2013 }} Tekniska Museet, retrieved 6 December 2011</ref>\n\nAfter some initial hesitation, [[Ruben Rausing]] became convinced that the invention was a good idea and ordered the project to be developed.<ref>Leander, Lars, ''Tetra Pak. A Vision Becomes Reality. A company history with a difference'', Lund: Tetra Pak International  1996 ({{ISBN|91-630-4789-6}}), p. 27f</ref> In March 1944 he filed for a patent, and in 1951 [[Tetra Pak]] was created as a subsidiary to [[\u00c5kerlund & Rausing]]. The [[tetrahedron]] package made [[Tetra Pak]] one of the world's most successful companies. The package is still sold today under the name of [[Tetra Classic Aseptic]].\n\n==Legacy==\nUpon visiting the Tetra Pak factory in Lund in the 1950s, Danish Nobel Prize winner and Physics professor [[Niels Bohr]] called the [[tetrahedron]] \"a perfect practical application of a mathematical problem\", and the invention lay the foundation of the [[Tetra Pak]] success saga.<ref>Andersson, Peter and Larsson, Tommy, ''Tetra. Historien om dynastin Rausing'', Stockholm: Norstedts 1998 ({{ISBN|91-7263-014-0}}), p. 23</ref> [[Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences|The Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences]] has called the Tetra Pak packaging system one of Sweden's most successful inventions of all times. The development of the triangular [[tetrahedron]] carton package, the  rectangular [[Tetra Brik]], was represented at the 2011 exhibition ''Hidden Heroes \u2013 The Genius of Everyday Things'' at the [[Science Museum (London)|London Science Museum/Vitra Design Museum]], celebrating \"the miniature marvels we couldn\u2019t live without\".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/uk/london/8876370/Miraculous-mundane-objects-from-Tetra-Pak-to-bubble-wrap.html Miraculous Mundane Objects: From Tetra Pak to Bubble Wrap] The Telegraph, retrieved  28 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/hiddenheroes Hidden Heroes \u2013 The Genius of Everyday Things] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222050535/http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/hiddenheroes |date=22 December 2011 }} The London Science Museum, retrieved 28 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.hidden-heroes.net/ Hidden Heroes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115151954/http://www.hidden-heroes.net/ |date=15 January 2017 }} The Vitra Design Museum, retrieved 28 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.iva.se/en/About-IVA/Histor/Tetra-Pak-/ Tetra Pak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109193328/http://www.iva.se/en/About-IVA/Histor/Tetra-Pak-/ |date=9 November 2014 }} Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences, IVA, retrieved 28 November 2011</ref>\n\nDespite the positive attention of the [[tetrahedron]], Wallenberg did not get due recognition for the invention until 1991, when he was awarded the Grand Gold Medal by [[Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences|The Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences]] for \"his ideas and efforts in the development of the packaging system Tetra Pak\".<ref>[http://www.tekniskamuseet.se/1/1781.html Tetra Pak (Swedish)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926034133/http://www.tekniskamuseet.se/1/1781.html |date=26 September 2013 }} Tekniska Museet, retrieved 6 December 2011</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wallenberg, Erik}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Karolinska Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Swedish inventors]]\n[[Category:Swedish scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century inventors]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Erik Wallenberg inventor of Tetra Pak first package.jpg|thumb|Erik Wallenberg with the tetrahedron package]]\n'''Erik Wallenberg''' (25 December 1915 \u2013 18 October 1999) was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] engineer. He is credited for inventing the [[Tetra Pak]] [[tetrahedron]] packaging in 1944.\n\n==Career==\nWallenberg had initially planned to join the Army as an officer, but fell ill during military training and had to abandon his plans. He was accepted at [[Karolinska Institutet]] medical school in [[Stockholm]], but decided to move to [[Lund]] and try to enter the medical school at [[Lund University]] instead.<ref>Andersson, Peter and Larsson, Tommy, ''Tetra. Historien om dynastin Rausing'', Stockholm: Norstedts 1998 ({{ISBN|91-7263-014-0}}), p. 13</ref>\n\nIn 1943, waiting to get accepted at [[Lund University]], Wallenberg got a job as lab assistant at [[\u00c5kerlund & Rausing]], a local firm manufacturing food packaging. When his manager got drafted in 1944, he became head of the research lab, aged 28.\n\nThe team had orders from the company owner [[Ruben Rausing]] to produce a viable packaging for milk that was cheap enough to compete with the current milk distribution system, based on loose milk sold in reusable glass bottles. The key to this was to use as little packaging material as possible. The research lab had tried and failed a number of different solutions. Finally, reportedly when ill with fever, Wallenberg got the idea of using one single sheet of paper rolled into a cylinder and folded from two different sides, creating a mathematical [[tetrahedron]].<ref>Andersson, Peter and Larsson, Tommy, ''Tetra. Historien om dynastin Rausing'', Stockholm: Norstedts 1998 ({{ISBN|91-7263-014-0}}), p. 18</ref> The volume created only needed to be sealed in three places and the packages could be produced in one subsequent sequence from one roll of paper, using a minimum of material, with a minimum of waste.<ref>[http://www.tekniskamuseet.se/1/1781.html Tetra Pak (Swedish)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926034133/http://www.tekniskamuseet.se/1/1781.html |date=26 September 2013 }} Tekniska Museet, retrieved 6 December 2011</ref>\n\nAfter some initial hesitation, [[Ruben Rausing]] became convinced that the invention was a good idea and ordered the project to be developed.<ref>Leander, Lars, ''Tetra Pak. A Vision Becomes Reality. A company history with a difference'', Lund: Tetra Pak International  1996 ({{ISBN|91-630-4789-6}}), p. 27f</ref> In March 1944 he filed for a patent, and in 1951 [[Tetra Pak]] was created as a subsidiary to [[\u00c5kerlund & Rausing]]. The [[tetrahedron]] package made [[Tetra Pak]] one of the world's most successful companies. The package is still sold today under the name of [[Tetra Classic Aseptic]].\n\n==Legacy==\nUpon visiting the Tetra Pak factory in Lund in the 1950s, Danish Nobel Prize winner and Physics professor [[Niels Bohr]] called the [[tetrahedron]] \"a perfect practical application of a mathematical problem\", and the invention lay the foundation of the [[Tetra Pak]] success saga.<ref>Andersson, Peter and Larsson, Tommy, ''Tetra. Historien om dynastin Rausing'', Stockholm: Norstedts 1998 ({{ISBN|91-7263-014-0}}), p. 23</ref> [[Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences|The Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences]] has called the Tetra Pak packaging system one of Sweden's most successful inventions of all times. The development of the triangular [[tetrahedron]] carton package, the  rectangular [[Tetra Brik]], was represented at the 2011 exhibition ''Hidden Heroes \u2013 The Genius of Everyday Things'' at the [[Science Museum (London)|London Science Museum/Vitra Design Museum]], celebrating \"the miniature marvels we couldn\u2019t live without\".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/uk/london/8876370/Miraculous-mundane-objects-from-Tetra-Pak-to-bubble-wrap.html Miraculous Mundane Objects: From Tetra Pak to Bubble Wrap] The Telegraph, retrieved  28 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/hiddenheroes Hidden Heroes \u2013 The Genius of Everyday Things] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222050535/http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/hiddenheroes |date=22 December 2011 }} The London Science Museum, retrieved 28 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.hidden-heroes.net/ Hidden Heroes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115151954/http://www.hidden-heroes.net/ |date=15 January 2017 }} The Vitra Design Museum, retrieved 28 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.iva.se/en/About-IVA/Histor/Tetra-Pak-/ Tetra Pak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109193328/http://www.iva.se/en/About-IVA/Histor/Tetra-Pak-/ |date=9 November 2014 }} Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences, IVA, retrieved 28 November 2011</ref>\n\nDespite the positive attention of the [[tetrahedron]], Wallenberg did not get due recognition for the invention until 1991, when he was awarded the Grand Gold Medal by [[Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences|The Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences]] for \"his ideas and efforts in the development of the packaging system Tetra Pak\".<ref>[http://www.tekniskamuseet.se/1/1781.html Tetra Pak (Swedish)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926034133/http://www.tekniskamuseet.se/1/1781.html |date=26 September 2013 }} Tekniska Museet, retrieved 6 December 2011</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wallenberg, Erik}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Karolinska Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Swedish inventors]]\n[[Category:Swedish scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century inventors]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erik_Wallenberg"}
{"title_page": "Walsall Wood railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name        = Walsall Wood\n| locale      = [[Walsall Wood]]\n| borough     = [[Metropolitan Borough of Walsall|Walsall]]\n| image       =\n| caption     =\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.6280|-1.9304|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| gridref     = SK047034\n| pregroup    = [[Midland Railway]]\n| postgroup   = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]\n| platforms   = 2\n| years1      = 1 July 1884\n| events1     = Opened<ref name=\"DS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/w/walsall_wood/index.shtml|title=Station Name: Walsall Wood|work=Disused Stations|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n| years3      = 31 March 1930\n| events3     = Closed<ref name=\"DS\" />\n| years4      = 1962\n| events4     = Line closed<ref name=\"WMBC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/walsall_wood_in_history.htm|work=Walsall MBC|title=Walsall Wood in History|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhills-history.fsnet.co.uk/walsall_wood.htm|title=Walsall Wood History|work=Brownhills History|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627121356/http://www.bhills-history.fsnet.co.uk/walsall_wood.htm|archivedate=27 June 2008}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Walsall Wood railway station''' was a station on the [[Midland Railway]] in England. It was opened in 1884, closed in March 1930<ref name=\"RABWM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railaroundbirmingham.co.uk/Stations/walsall_wood.php|title=Walsall Wood Station|work=Rail Around Birmingham and the West Midlands|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> for passenger use although the odd [[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]] would serve the station from [[Birmingham New Street]] and [[Walsall]].\n\nThe line from Walsall Wood to Brownhills Watling Street closed first along in 1960 and the section from Walsall Wood to Aldridge closed five years later in 1965 at the same time as Aldridge railway station closed. The station building was later demolished after falling into derelict condition.\n\nThe trackbed from Walsall Wood to Aldridge has since become a landfill site although the original road bridges near Coppice Road and Queen Street/Vigo Road are still in place and take the roads over the old trackbed. The section towards Brownhills Watling Street has become a housing estate. Oak Park also occupy sections of the old trackbed for leisure use and the original station is now a playground.\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{rail line|previous=[[Aldridge railway station|Aldridge]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next=[[Brownhills Watling Street railway station|Brownhills Watling Street]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[Midland Railway]]<br /><small>[[Aldridge to Brownhills Branch]]</small> |col={{MR colour}} }}\n{{end box}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{West Midlands railway stations|disused}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Walsall]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1884]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1930]]\n[[Category:Former Midland Railway stations]]\n\n\n{{WestMidlands-struct-stub}}\n{{WestMidlands-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name        = Walsall Wood\n| locale      = [[Walsall Wood]]\n| borough     = [[Metropolitan Borough of Walsall|Walsall]]\n| image       =\n| caption     =\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.6280|-1.9304|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| gridref     = SK047034\n| pregroup    = [[Midland Railway]]\n| postgroup   = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]\n| platforms   = 2\n| years1      = 1 July 1884\n| events1     = Opened<ref name=\"DS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/w/walsall_wood/index.shtml|title=Station Name: Walsall Wood|work=Disused Stations|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n| years3      = 31 March 1930\n| events3     = Closed<ref name=\"DS\" />\n| years4      = 1962\n| events4     = Line closed<ref name=\"WMBC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/walsall_wood_in_history.htm|work=Walsall MBC|title=Walsall Wood in History|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhills-history.fsnet.co.uk/walsall_wood.htm|title=Walsall Wood History|work=Brownhills History|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627121356/http://www.bhills-history.fsnet.co.uk/walsall_wood.htm|archivedate=27 June 2008}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Walsall Wood railway station''' was a station on the [[Midland Railway]] in England. It was opened in 1884, closed in March 1930<ref name=\"RABWM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railaroundbirmingham.co.uk/Stations/walsall_wood.php|title=Walsall Wood Station|work=Rail Around Birmingham and the West Midlands|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> for passenger use although the odd [[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]] would serve the station from [[Birmingham New Street]] and [[Walsall]]. \n\nThe line from Walsall Wood to Brownhills Watling Street closed first along in 1960 and the section from Walsall Wood to Aldridge closed five years later in 1965 at the same time as Aldridge railway station closed. The station building was later demolished after falling into derelict condition. \n\nThe trackbed from Walsall Wood to Aldridge has since become a landfill site although the original road bridges near Coppice Road and Queen Street/Vigo Road are still in place and take the roads over the old trackbed. The section towards Brownhills Watling Street has become a housing estate. Oak Park also occupy sections of the old trackbed for leisure use and the original station is now a playground. \n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{rail line|previous=[[Aldridge railway station|Aldridge]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next=[[Brownhills Watling Street railway station|Brownhills Watling Street]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[Midland Railway]]<br /><small>[[Aldridge t