{"title_page": "William Allen Walsh", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name=William Allen Walsh\n| birthname=William Allen Walsh\n| image=\n| imagesize=150px\n| caption=\n| birth_date={{birth date|df=yes|1887|8|20}}\n| birth_place=[[Kingston, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date={{death date and age|1940|10|18|1887|8|20|df=yes}}\n| death_place=\n| spouse=Edith Thompson<br />m.&nbsp;27&nbsp;December&nbsp;1916<ref name=CPG>{{cite book | title=Canadian Parliamentary Guide | first=A.L. | last=Normandin | year=1936}}</ref>\n| residence=\n| riding=[[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]]\n| predecessor=[[Robert Smeaton White]]\n| successor=[[Fred Whitman]]\n| term_start=October 1935\n| term_end=March 1940\n| profession=school principal, school superintendent, teacher\n| party=[[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]]\n| footnotes=\n| religion=\n| website=\n|}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''William Allen Walsh''' (20 August 1887 \u2013 18 October 1940) was a [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]]. He was born in [[Kingston, Ontario]] and became a school principal, school superintendent and teacher, primarily at the Protestant Strathcona Academy in the Montreal suburb of Outremont.\n\nHe was first elected to Parliament at the [[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]] riding in the [[1935 Canadian federal election|1935 general election]]. After serving one term, the [[18th Canadian Parliament]], Walsh entered the [[1940 Canadian federal election|March 1940 election]] under the Conservative-based [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)#National Government label|National Government party]] banner but was defeated by [[Fred Whitman]] of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal party]]. Walsh died months later, on 18 October 1940.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=2047}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, William Allen}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Quebec]]\n[[Category:National Government candidates in the 1940 Canadian federal election]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942) MPs]]\n\n\n{{Conservative18671942-Quebec-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox CanadianMP\n| name=William Allen Walsh\n| birthname=William Allen Walsh\n| image=\n| imagesize=150px\n| caption=\n| birth_date={{birth date|df=yes|1887|8|20}}\n| birth_place=[[Kingston, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date={{death date and age|1940|10|18|1887|8|20|df=yes}}\n| death_place=\n| spouse=Edith Thompson<br />m.&nbsp;27&nbsp;December&nbsp;1916<ref name=CPG>{{cite book | title=Canadian Parliamentary Guide | first=A.L. | last=Normandin | year=1936}}</ref>\n| residence=\n| riding=[[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]]\n| predecessor=[[Robert Smeaton White]]\n| successor=[[Fred Whitman]]\n| term_start=October 1935\n| term_end=March 1940\n| profession=school principal, school superintendent, teacher\n| party=[[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]]\n| footnotes=\n| religion=\n| website=\n|}}{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n'''William Allen Walsh''' (20 August 1887 \u2013 18 October 1940) was a [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative]] member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]]. He was born in [[Kingston, Ontario]] and became a school principal, school superintendent and teacher, primarily at the Protestant Strathcona Academy in the Montreal suburb of Outremont.\n\nHe was first elected to Parliament at the [[Mount Royal (electoral district)|Mount Royal]] riding in the [[1935 Canadian federal election|1935 general election]]. After serving one term, the [[18th Canadian Parliament]], Walsh entered the [[1940 Canadian federal election|March 1940 election]] under the Conservative-based [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)#National Government label|National Government party]] banner but was defeated by [[Fred Whitman]] of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal party]]. Walsh died months later, on 18 October 1940.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=2047}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, William Allen}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Quebec]]\n[[Category:National Government candidates in the 1940 Canadian federal election]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942) MPs]]\n\n\n{{Conservative18671942-Quebec-MP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Allen_Walsh"}
{"title_page": "Richard Walter (writer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Richard Walter\n| image       = Richard Walter UCLA Screenwriting Program Chairman.jpg\n| alt         =\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| nationality = American\n| yearsactive = \n| occupation  = [[Author]], [[educator]], [[screenwriter]], [[Pundit|commentator]], [[consultant]]\n| known_for   = ''Screenwriting: The Art, Craft and Business of Film and Television Writing''\n}}\n\n'''Richard Walter''' is an American [[author]], [[educator]], [[screenwriter]], [[Pundit|commentator]], [[consultant]], and [[chairman]] of the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] graduate program in [[screenwriting]].<ref name=UCLAfaculty>[http://www.tft.ucla.edu/faculty/richard-walter/ UCLA faculty bio]</ref>\n\nHe has written several  works, including the ''Essentials of Screenwriting'', published in June 2010,<ref name=EssentialsofScreenwriting>[http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780452296275,00.html?strSrchSql=richard+walter+essentials+of+screenwriting/Essentials_of_Screenwriting_Richard_Walter/ Penguin Group publishing]</ref><ref name=Screenplay.com>[http://www.screenplay.com/t-RWalter_Interview.aspx/ ''Screenplay.com'' interview]</ref> and the novels ''Escape from Film School'' and ''Barry and the Persuasions''. Other publications include screenwriting books ''The Whole Picture: Strategies for Screenwriting Success in the New Hollywood'' and ''Screenwriting: The Art, Craft and Business of Film and Television Writing''.\n\nHis sister is actress [[Jessica Walter]]. Walter's family is [[Jewish]].\n\n==Career==\nWalter lectures on screenwriting and storytelling throughout North America and the world. He has written numerous feature assignments for the major studios and has sold material to all of the [[Big Three television networks]]. He has also written many informational, educational and corporate films, and is a 30-year member of the [[Writers Guild of America, West|Writers Guild of America]]. He has conducted [[master class]]es in London, Paris, Jerusalem, Madrid, Rio de Janeiro, Mexico City, Beijing and Hong Kong.\n\nWalter is also a [[popular culture|pop culture]] critic and media [[pundit (expert)|pundit]] on entertainment history-related topics, such as [[anti-Americanism]] and [[Hollywood]],<ref name=npr>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6625002 ''NPR'' December 2006]</ref> screenwriting as a career,<ref name=scriptmag>[http://www.scriptmag.com/2010/07/06/qa-with-ucla-screenwriting-chairman-richard-walter/ ''Scriptmag.com'' interview]</ref> [[film production]]<ref name=businessinsider>[http://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-prepare-for-an-interview-in-film-production-2010-11# ''BusinessInsider.com'' November 2010]</ref> and politics.<ref name=political>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/richard-walter/post_1509_b_802902.html ''Huffington Post'' December 2010]</ref> Walter is also a court authorized expert in [[intellectual property]] law,<ref name=hill.com>[http://www2.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=THEHILLLEG.story&STORY=/www/story/01-30-2007/0004516300&EDATE=TUE+Jan+30+2007,+01:13+PM/ ''TheHill.com'' January 2007]</ref> in particular [[plagiarism]] and [[copyright infringement]].\n\n==Students==\nStudents from Walter\u2019s screenwriting program at UCLA have written projects for [[Steven Spielberg]], and many successful Hollywood  productions,<ref name=uclanews>[http://www.tft.ucla.edu/news/announcement/74-richard-walter-tft-professor/ UCLA news] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026101855/http://www.tft.ucla.edu/news/announcement/74-richard-walter-tft-professor/ |date=26 October 2008 }}</ref> including three [[Academy Award]]s for best screenplay: [[Dustin Lance Black]] for [[Milk (film)|''Milk'']] and [[Alexander Payne]] for ''[[Sideways]]'' and [[The Descendants]].<ref name=UCLApub>[http://spotlight.ucla.edu/faculty/rich-walter_screenwriter/ UCLA ''Spotlight'' 2006]</ref> Other past students of the UCLA program under Walter's direction include these television and film screenwriters:\n* [[Sacha Gervasi]] - ''[[The Terminal (film)|The Terminal]]''\n* [[Dan Mazeau]] - ''[[Wrath of the Titans]]''\n* [[Felicia Henderson]] - ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]'', ''[[Gossip Girl]]'', ''Soul Food'' (television series), ''Everybody Hates Chris'', ''Fresh Prince of Bel-Air'', ''Single Ladies''\n* Caroline Williams - ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', ''Modern Family''\n* [[Don Payne (writer)|Don Payne]] \u2013 ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[Fantastic Four: Rise of the Silver Surfer]]'', ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]'' (2011) and its sequel ''[[Thor: The Dark World]]''\n* [[Paul Castro]] - ''[[August Rush]]''\n* [[Tom Shadyac]] - ''I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry'', ''[[Bruce Almighty]]'', ''Dragonfly'', ''Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'', ''Ace Ventura: Pet Detective'', ''[[Liar Liar]]''\n* [[David Koepp]] - ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'', ''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]'', ''[[Carlito\u2019s Way]]'', ''War of the Worlds'', ''Angels & Demons''\n* [[Gregory Widen]] - ''[[Highlander (film)|Highlander]]'', ''[[Backdraft (film)|Backdraft]]''\n* [[Scott Rosenberg]] - ''Beautiful Girls'', ''Things to Do in Denver When You\u2019re Dead'', ''High Fidelity''\n* [[Scott Kosar]] - ''[[The Amityville Horror (2005 film)|Amityville Horror]]'', ''Texas Chainsaw Massacre'', ''The Crazies'', ''The Machinist''\n* [[Audrey Wells]] - ''The Game Plan'', ''[[Shall We Dance? (2004 film)|Shall We Dance?]]'', ''[[Under the Tuscan Sun (film)|Under the Tuscan Sun]]'', ''The Kid'', ''George of the Jungle'', ''The Truth About Cats & Dogs''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://richardwalter.com/ Richard Walter's Official Website]\n*{{IMDb name|id=2170580|name=Richard Walter}}\n*[http://www.tft.ucla.edu/ UCLA School of Theater, Film and Television]\n*[http://www.wga.org/ Writers Guild of America]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walter, Richard}}\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Screenwriting instructors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Richard Walter\n| image       = Richard Walter UCLA Screenwriting Program Chairman.jpg\n| alt         =\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| nationality = American\n| yearsactive = \n| occupation  = [[Author]], [[educator]], [[screenwriter]], [[Pundit|commentator]], [[consultant]]\n| known_for   = ''Screenwriting: The Art, Craft and Business of Film and Television Writing''\n}}\n\n'''Richard Walter''' is an American [[author]], [[educator]], [[screenwriter]], [[Pundit|commentator]], [[consultant]], and [[chairman]] of the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] graduate program in [[screenwriting]].<ref name=UCLAfaculty>[http://www.tft.ucla.edu/faculty/richard-walter/ UCLA faculty bio]</ref>\n\nHe has written several  works, including the ''Essentials of Screenwriting'', published in June 2010,<ref name=EssentialsofScreenwriting>[http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780452296275,00.html?strSrchSql=richard+walter+essentials+of+screenwriting/Essentials_of_Screenwriting_Richard_Walter/ Penguin Group publishing]</ref><ref name=Screenplay.com>[http://www.screenplay.com/t-RWalter_Interview.aspx/ ''Screenplay.com'' interview]</ref> and the novels ''Escape from Film School'' and ''Barry and the Persuasions''. Other publications include screenwriting books ''The Whole Picture: Strategies for Screenwriting Success in the New Hollywood'' and ''Screenwriting: The Art, Craft and Business of Film and Television Writing''.\n\nHis sister is actress [[Jessica Walter]]. Walter's family is [[Jewish]].\n\n==Career==\nWalter lectures on screenwriting and storytelling throughout North America and the world. He has written numerous feature assignments for the major studios and has sold material to all of the [[Big Three television networks]]. He has also written many informational, educational and corporate films, and is a 30-year member of the [[Writers Guild of America, West|Writers Guild of America]]. He has conducted [[master class]]es in London, Paris, Jerusalem, Madrid, Rio de Janeiro, Mexico City, Beijing and Hong Kong.\n\nWalter is also a [[popular culture|pop culture]] critic and media [[pundit (expert)|pundit]] on entertainment history-related topics, such as [[anti-Americanism]] and [[Hollywood]],<ref name=npr>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6625002 ''NPR'' December 2006]</ref> screenwriting as a career,<ref name=scriptmag>[http://www.scriptmag.com/2010/07/06/qa-with-ucla-screenwriting-chairman-richard-walter/ ''Scriptmag.com'' interview]</ref> [[film production]]<ref name=businessinsider>[http://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-prepare-for-an-interview-in-film-production-2010-11# ''BusinessInsider.com'' November 2010]</ref> and politics.<ref name=political>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/richard-walter/post_1509_b_802902.html ''Huffington Post'' December 2010]</ref> Walter is also a court authorized expert in [[intellectual property]] law,<ref name=hill.com>[http://www2.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=THEHILLLEG.story&STORY=/www/story/01-30-2007/0004516300&EDATE=TUE+Jan+30+2007,+01:13+PM/ ''TheHill.com'' January 2007]</ref> in particular [[plagiarism]] and [[copyright infringement]].\n\n==Students==\nStudents from Walter\u2019s screenwriting program at UCLA have written projects for [[Steven Spielberg]], and many successful Hollywood  productions,<ref name=uclanews>[http://www.tft.ucla.edu/news/announcement/74-richard-walter-tft-professor/ UCLA news] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026101855/http://www.tft.ucla.edu/news/announcement/74-richard-walter-tft-professor/ |date=26 October 2008 }}</ref> including three [[Academy Award]]s for best screenplay: [[Dustin Lance Black]] for [[Milk (film)|''Milk'']] and [[Alexander Payne]] for ''[[Sideways]]'' and [[The Descendants]].<ref name=UCLApub>[http://spotlight.ucla.edu/faculty/rich-walter_screenwriter/ UCLA ''Spotlight'' 2006]</ref> Other past students of the UCLA program under Walter's direction include these television and film screenwriters:\n* [[Sacha Gervasi]] - ''[[The Terminal (film)|The Terminal]]''\n* [[Dan Mazeau]] - ''[[Wrath of the Titans]]''\n* [[Felicia Henderson]] - ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]'', ''[[Gossip Girl]]'', ''Soul Food'' (television series), ''Everybody Hates Chris'', ''Fresh Prince of Bel-Air'', ''Single Ladies''\n* Caroline Williams - ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', ''Modern Family''\n* [[Don Payne (writer)|Don Payne]] \u2013 ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[Fantastic Four: Rise of the Silver Surfer]]'', ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]'' (2011) and its sequel ''[[Thor: The Dark World]]''\n* [[Paul Castro]] - ''[[August Rush]]''\n* [[Tom Shadyac]] - ''I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry'', ''[[Bruce Almighty]]'', ''Dragonfly'', ''Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'', ''Ace Ventura: Pet Detective'', ''[[Liar Liar]]''\n* [[David Koepp]] - ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'', ''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]'', ''[[Carlito\u2019s Way]]'', ''War of the Worlds'', ''Angels & Demons''\n* [[Gregory Widen]] - ''[[Highlander (film)|Highlander]]'', ''[[Backdraft (film)|Backdraft]]''\n* [[Scott Rosenberg]] - ''Beautiful Girls'', ''Things to Do in Denver When You\u2019re Dead'', ''High Fidelity''\n* [[Scott Kosar]] - ''[[The Amityville Horror (2005 film)|Amityville Horror]